A087553.name: Squares in which the neighboring digits differ at most by 1. Neighbors of 1 are 0 and 2, neighbors of 0 are 1 and 9.

A087554.name: a(n) = smallest number k >= n such that nk + 1 is a prime.

A087555.name: a(n) = largest prime that is the concatenation of two numbers whose sum is n.

A087556.name: a(n) = smallest prime that is the concatenation of two numbers whose sum is n.

A087557.name: a(n) = smallest prime that is the concatenation of two numbers whose product is n.

A087558.name: a(n) = largest prime that is the concatenation of two numbers whose product is n.

A087559.name: Rearrangement of natural numbers such that n*a(n) + 1 is a prime.

A087560.name: Smallest m > n such that gcd(m, n^2) = n.

A087561.name: Number of solutions to x^2 + 2y^2 == 0 (mod n).
formula: Multiplicative with a(2^e) = 2^e, a(p^e) = p^(2*floor(e/2)) for p - 2 == +-3 (mod 8), a(p^e) = ((p-1)*e+p)*p^(e-1) for p - 2 == +-1 (mod 8). - _Andrew Howroyd_, Jul 16 2018

A087562.name: Primes such that the next n successive differences are identical.

A087564.name: a(n) = smallest prime of the form n*(n+1)*(n+2)*...*(n+k) + 1, or 0 if no such prime exists.

A087565.name: a(n) = smallest k such that n*(n+1)*(n+2)...(n+k) + 1 is prime, or -1 if no prime of such form exists.

A087566.name: a(n) = index of the first occurrence of n in A087565, or 0 if n is not a term of A087565.

A087571.name: Smallest prime which has the form of the concatenation n, n-1, n-2, n-3, .., n-k for some k < n, or 0 if no such prime exists.

A087572.name: Smallest prime of the form n + (n-1) + (n-2) + ...(n-k), k < n, or 0 if no such prime exists.

A087573.name: Smallest number k such that prime(4) + k, prime(5) + k, ..., prime(n+3) + k are all prime.

A087574.name: a(1) = 1, then the smallest number such that the n-th partial concatenation has a prime signature of n.

A087575.name: Smallest prime p such that 2+p^n is a prime, or 0 if no such prime exists.

A087576.name: Smallest number k > 1 such that k^n+2 is prime.

A087577.name: Smallest number k such that k^n + 3 is a prime.

A087580.name: Primes with n-th successive differences a multiple of Fibonacci(n+1). a(n)-a(n-1) == 0 (mod F(n+1)), F(n+1) = A000045(n+1).

A087581.name: Primes such that successive differences are increasing palindromes.

A087582.name: Primes such that successive differences are distinct palindromes.

A087583.name: Distinct primes such that the absolute values of successive differences are distinct palindromes. a(n+1) is chosen to be < a(n) if such a prime exists, minimizing a(n)-a(n+1); otherwise the minimal a(n+1) > a(n) is chosen.

A087585.name: a(1) = 12; a(n) = smallest multiple of a(n-1), not == 0 (mod 10) beginning with the digit reversal of a(n-1).

A087586.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = smallest square beginning with the digit reversal of a(n-1).

A087588.name: a(1) = 4, a(n) = smallest square beginning with the digit reversal of a(n-1).

A087590.name: a(1) = 9, a(n) = smallest square beginning with the digit reversal of a(n-1). a(n) > a(n-1) and a(n) is not == 0 (mod 10).

A087592.name: Primes whose successive differences are increasing power of 2: a(1) = 2, a(n+1) = a(n) + 2^k; a(n+1) prime, k minimal and greater than the index for the previous term.

A087593.name: Define dd(n) = the number formed by concatenating the absolute difference of successive digits. Sequence contains primes p such that dd(p) is also prime. (Primes in which the number formed by successive digit difference is also a prime.).

A087594.name: Define dd(n) = the number formed by concatenating the absolute difference of successive digits. Sequence contains primes p such that dd(p)=q is a prime, dd(q) is also a prime = r and so on until a single-digit prime (2,3,5,7) arises. (Primes in which the number formed by successive digit differences are primes at every step until a single-digit prime is obtained.).

A087595.name: Smallest n-digit member of A087593. Define dd(k) = the number formed by concatenating the absolute difference of successive digits of k. Sequence contains smallest n-digit prime p such that dd(p) is also prime.

A087596.name: Largest n-digit member of A087593. Define dd(k) = the number formed by concatenating the absolute difference of successive digits of k. Sequence contains largest n-digit prime p such that dd(p) is also prime.

A087597.name: Define dd(k) = the number formed by concatenating the absolute difference of successive digits of k. Triangular numbers t such that dd(t) is also a triangular number. (Triangular number in which the number formed by successive digit difference is also a triangular number.).

A087598.name: Define dd(k) = the number formed by concatenating the absolute difference of successive digits of k. Triangular numbers t such that dd(t)= say, r, dd(r) = s and so on Then t,r,s etc. are triangular numbers until a single-digit triangular number (0,1,3,or 6 ) arises. (Triangular number in which the number formed by successive digit difference is also a triangular number at every step which finally ends up in a one-digit triangular number.).

A087599.name: Smallest n-digit member of A087597, or 0 if no such number exists.

A087600.name: Largest n-digit member of A087597, or 0 if no such number exists.

A087601.name: Primes occurring as lesser side of Heronian triangle (sides are consecutive integers, area and inradius are integers).
formula: Prime elements of A016064. Alternatively, primes p such that 3*(p+1)^2-12 is a square, i.e., p+1 belongs to A003500. - _Max Alekseyev_, May 14 2010

A087602.name: Primes occurring as larger side of Heronian triangle (sides are consecutive integers, area and inradius are integers).
formula: p, p-1 and p-2 are sides of Heronian triangle.
Primes p such that 3*(p-1)^2-12 is a square, i.e., p-1 belongs to A003500. - _Max Alekseyev_, May 14 2010

A087604.name: Smallest k such that n times concatenation of k with itself followed by a 3 is a prime, or 0 if no such number exists.

A087605.name: Smallest k such that n times concatenation of k with itself followed by a 7 is a prime, or 0 if no such number exists.
formula: Minimal k such that k*(10^(l*n)-1)/(10^l-1)*10+7 is prime, where l is the length of k; and 0 if no such prime exists. - _Max Alekseyev_, Feb 11 2005

A087606.name: Smallest k such that n times concatenation of k with itself followed by a 9 is a prime, or 0 if no such number exists.

A087607.name: Primes arising in A087606, or 0 if A087606(k) = 0.

A087608.name: Primes arising in A087605, or 0 if A087605(n) = 0.

A087609.name: Primes arising in A087604, or 0 if A087604(n) = 0.

A087610.name: Number of (-1,0,1) polynomials of degree-n irreducible over the integers.

A087612.name: A divisibility sequence derived from Lehmer's polynomial x^10+x^9-x^7-x^6-x^5-x^4-x^3+x+1. Square root of the terms in A059928.

A087613.name: Number of labeled acyclic preferences/voting outcomes, indifference and undecidedness/incompleteness permitted (Social Choice Theory).

A087614.name: Number of unlabeled acyclic preferences/voting outcomes, indifference and undecidedness/incompleteness permitted (Social Choice Theory).

A087615.name: Number of labeled cyclic preferences/voting outcomes, indifference and undecidedness/incompleteness permitted (Social Choice Theory).

A087616.name: Number of unlabeled cyclic preferences/voting outcomes, indifference and undecidedness/incompleteness permitted (Social Choice Theory).

A087617.name: Gabcke sequence: a(0)=1; (n+1) a(n+1) = Sum_{k=0..n} 2^(4k+1) |E(2k+2)| a(n-k), where |E(2k+2)| are Euler numbers (E(2k)=(-1)^k A000364(k)).

A087618.name: a(n) is the number of pair of consecutive numbers (k,k+1) with k<=10^n such that k and k+1 are both squarefree.

A087621.name: (1,1) entry of powers of the orthogonal design shown below.

A087622.name: Order of letters on Dvorak typewriter (or computer) keyboard.

A087623.name: Triangle read by rows: T(m,n) is the cardinality of the set {k in [1,n-1] : gcd(k,n)=m}.

A087624.name: a(n)=0 if n is prime, A001221(n) otherwise.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} x^(2*prime(k)) / (1 - x^prime(k)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 13 2021

A087625.name: Number of primes in the ring Z_n.
formula: a(n)=Sum'_{p|n} A087623(p, n), where the sum is over all primes p < n, p | n.
a(p^k q)=p^{k-2}(p-1)(p+q-1) if p, q primes (q!=p), k>=2.
a(pq)=p+q-2 if p, q primes, p!=q.
A(p^k q^h)=p^{k-2}q^{h-2}(p-1)(q-1)(p+q) if p, q primes (q!=p),

A087626.name: Expansion of 2/(1-2x+sqrt(1-4x+4x^3)).
formula: HANKEL transform is A006720(n+2). HANKEL transform with 0 prepended is -A051138.
INVERT transform of A157003. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 28 2020

A087630.name: Number of n-digit primes ending in 1 in base 10.

A087631.name: Number of n-digit primes ending in 3 in base 10.

A087632.name: Number of n-digit primes ending in 7 in base 10.

A087633.name: Number of n-digit primes ending in 9 in base 10.

A087634.name: Primes p such that the equation phi(x) = 4p has a solution, where phi is the totient function.

A087635.name: a(n) = S(n,3) where S(n,m) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n,k)*fibonacci(m*k).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} C(n,k)*Fibonacci(k)*Lucas(n-k). - _Ross La Haye_, Aug 14 2006

A087638.name: Number of lunar primes with <= n digits.

A087639.name: E.g.f.: Product_{m >= 1} (1+x^(2*m)/(2*m)) (even powers only).
formula: a(n) ~ 2*exp(-gamma/2) * (2*n)! / (Pi*sqrt(n)), where gamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant A001620. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jul 23 2019

A087640.name: To obtain a(n+1), take the square of the n-th partial sum, minus the sum of the first n squared terms, then divide this difference by a(n); for all n>1, starting with a(0)=1, a(1)=1.

A087641.name: Start of the first sequence of exactly n consecutive pairs of twin primes.

A087642.name: Sequence of squarefree n such that Q(sqrt(n)) has no element with a fully periodical continued fraction of period 1.

A087643.name: Nonsquare positive integers n such that the fundamental unit of quadratic field Q(sqrt(n)) has norm 1.

A087644.name: Triangle T(n,k) (n >= 2, 1 <= k <= n) read by rows: (1/2) times number of linearly inducible orderings of n points in k-dimensional Euclidean space.

A087646.name: a(n) is the first term of the first run of exactly n non-perfect-powers.

A087647.name: Triangle of 3-Narayana numbers, N(n,k), for n >= 1, 0 <= k <= 2n-2.
formula: For 0<=k<=2n-2, N(n, k) := Sum[2*(-1)^(k-j)*C(3*n+1, k-j)*C(n+j, n)*C(n+j+1, n)*C(n+j+2, n)/(n+1)^2/(n+2), {j, 0, k}] = Sum[(-1)^(k-j)*C(3*n+1, k-j)*a(n, j), {j, 0, k}] where a(m, n) is an entry in the triangle of A056939.

A087649.name: (1/2)*(Bell(n+2)-Bell(n+1)+Bell(n)).
formula: G.f.: (1-x+x^2)/(2*x*Q(0)) - 1/(2*x) + 1/2, where Q(k)= 1 - x - x/(1 - x*(2*k+1)/(1 - x - x/(1 - x*(2*k+2)/Q(k+1)))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 13 2013

A087650.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} (-1)^(n-k)*Bell(k).
formula: a(n) = (-1)^n + Bell(n) - A000296(n), with Bell(n) = A000110(n). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Dec 01 2003
G.f.: 1/(1+x)/W(0), where W(k) = 1 - x/(1 - x*(k+1)/W(k+1) ); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Nov 10 2014
a(0) = 1; a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n-1} binomial(n,k) * a(k-1). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Mar 04 2021

A087651.name: Sequence of primorials P# (cf. A002110) such that j*P# has twin prime neighbors for some j with 0 < j < prime following P.

A087652.name: Product of the nonprime divisors of n.
formula: a(n) = 1 if n=1 or n is prime; a(n) = n if n=1 or n is semiprime (A001358).
If n is squarefree, then a(n) = n^(d(n)/2-1), where d(n) is the number of divisors of n (A000005). (End)
a(p^e) = p^((e^2+e-2)/2) for p prime, e > 0. - _Bernard Schott_, Jun 08 2020

A087653.name: Maximum difference between exponents in n-th cyclotomic polynomial.
formula: a(p) = a(p*q) = p-1 for primes p < q (by Hong et al.). - _Jonathan Sondow_, Jan 09 2014

A087654.name: Decimal expansion of D(1) where D(x) is the Dawson function.

A087655.name: a[n] = a[abs[n - a[n-1]]] + a[abs[n - a[n-2]]]+ a[abs[n - a[n-3]]]

A087656.name: Let f be defined on the rationals by f(p/q) =(p+1)/(q+1)=p_{1}/q_{1} where (p_{1},q_{1})=1. Let f^k(p/q)=p_{k}/q_{k} where (p_{k},q_{k})=1. Sequence gives least k such that p_{k}-q_{k} = 1 starting at n.
formula: If p is prime a(p+1)=p-1; it appears that a(n)=(n-1)/2 iff n is in A079148 or in A053177.

A087660.name: Values of a certain hypergeometric function. Not known to be always integer-valued.

A087661.name: Values of a certain hypergeometric function. Not known to be always integer-valued.

A087662.name: Values of a certain hypergeometric function. Not known to be always integer-valued.

A087664.name: Consider recurrence b(0) = n/4, b(k) = b(k-1)*floor(b(k-1)); sequence gives number of steps to reach an integer, or -1 if no integer is ever reached.

A087665.name: Consider recurrence b(0) = n/4, b(k) = b(k-1)*floor(b(k-1)); sequence gives first integer reached, or -1 if no integer is ever reached.

A087666.name: Consider recurrence b(0) = n/3, b(k+1) = b(k)*floor(b(k)); a(n) is the least k such that b(k) is an integer, or -1 if no integer is ever reached.
formula: a(n)=0 iff n == 0 (mod 3), a(n)==1 iff n == 1 or 2 (mod 3^2), a(n)=2 iff n == 14,22,25,26 (mod 3^3). In general a(n)=m iff n == x (mod 3^m) where x pertains to a set of 2^m distinct elements included in {1,2,...,(3^m)-1}. Conjecture: a(6) + a(7) + a(8) + ... + a(n) = 2n + O(sqrt(n)). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Sep 24 2012

A087669.name: The smallest index m such that b(m) is an integer, where b(0)=(2n+1)/n and b(k+1)=b(k)*floor(b(k)) for k>=0.

A087670.name: The first integer in the sequence defined by b(0)=(2n+1)/n and b(k+1)=b(k)*floor(b(k)) for k>=0.

A087671.name: Number of subsets S of {0,1,2,...,n-1} which are idempotent under squaring modulo n, where S*S mod n = {x*y mod n|x,y in S}.

A087672.name: n = k^2 - (reversal of k)^2 for two different values of k.

A087673.name: a(n) is smallest number m such that (m = product of n primes, not necessarily distinct ones) and all divisors of m are lucky numbers.

A087674.name: Value of the n-th Eulerian polynomial (cf. A008292) evaluated at x=-2.
formula: O.g.f.: Sum_{n>=0} n! * x^n / Product_{k=1..n} (1 + 3*k*x). [_Paul D. Hanna_, Jul 20 2011]
G.f.: 1/Q(0), where Q(k)= 1 - x*(k+1)/(1 + x*(2*k+2)/Q(k+1)); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 20 2013

A087675.name: Consider recurrence b(0) = (2n+1)/2, b(n) = b(0)*floor(b(n-1)); sequence gives first integer reached.
formula: The even-indexed terms are given by A007742.

A087676.name: Consider recurrence b(0) = n/3, b(n) = b(0)*floor(b(n-1)); sequence gives number of steps to reach an integer, or -1 if no integer is ever reached.

A087677.name: Consider recurrence b(0) = n/3, b(n) = b(0)*floor(b(n-1)); sequence gives first integer reached, or -1 if no integer is ever reached.

A087678.name: Numbers n such that n + 9 and n - 9 are both prime.

A087679.name: Numbers k such that both k+2 and k-2 are prime.

A087680.name: Numbers n such that n + 4 and n - 4 are both prime.

A087681.name: Numbers n such that n + 6 and n - 6 are both prime.

A087682.name: Numbers n such that n + 8 and n - 8 are both prime.

A087683.name: Numbers n such that n + 10 and n - 10 are both prime.

A087684.name: Consecutive repeating elements in sequence A006158.

A087685.name: Primes p such that 5^p - 4^p is composite.

A087686.name: Elements of A004001 that repeat consecutively.

A087687.name: Number of solutions to x^2 + y^2 + z^2 == 0 (mod n).
formula: a(2^k) = 2^(k + ceiling(k/2)). For odd primes p, a(p^(2k-1)) = p^(3k-2)*(p^k + p^(k-1) - 1) and a(p^(2k)) = p^(3k-1)*(p^(k+1) + p^k - 1). - _Martin Fuller_, Jan 26 2009
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ (4*zeta(3))/(15*zeta(4)) * n^3 + O(n^2 * log(n)) (Calderón and de Velasco, 2000). - _Amiram Eldar_, Mar 04 2021

A087688.name: a(n) = number of solutions to x^3 - x == 0 (mod n).
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = 3 for p an odd prime, a(2^1) = 2, a(2^2) = 3, a(2^e) = 5 for e >= 3. - _Eric M. Schmidt_, Apr 08 2013

A087689.name: Numerators of successive partial sums of sum(1/(2^n-1)).

A087690.name: Denominators of successive partial sums of sum(1/(2^n-1)).

A087691.name: Squares of primes of the form 4n+3.
formula: a(n) ~ 4n^2 * (log n)^2. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Sep 20 2016

A087692.name: Number of cubes in multiplicative group modulo n.

A087693.name: Lesser twin prime p such that 2^p-1 is composite.

A087694.name: Number of solutions to x^2 + xy + y^2 == 0 (mod n).
formula: Multiplicative with a(3^e) = 3^e, a(p^e) = ((p-1)*e+p)*p^(e-1) if p mod 3 = 1, a(p^e) = p^(2*floor(e/2)) if p mod 3 = 2. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Sep 27 2003

A087695.name: Numbers n such that n + 3 and n - 3 are both prime.

A087696.name: Numbers n such that n + 5 and n - 5 are both prime.

A087697.name: Numbers k such that k + 7 and k - 7 are both prime.

A087698.name: Triangle read by rows, giving T(n,k) = maximum number of examples (Boolean inputs) at Hamming distance 2 for symmetric Boolean functions that can have different outputs.
formula: T(n, N) = ((N-n)^2 + n^2 - N) * C(N, n) / (N^2 - N) n is the term for the series containing N+1 terms
Except for (n,k) = (1,0) the formula T(n,k) = C(n,k) - 2*C(n-1,n-k-1) + 2*C(n-2,n-k-2), where C(n,k) = n!/(k!*(n-k)!) for 0 <= k <= n, otherwise 0, appears to give the correct table entries.

Appears to equal A159853, the Riordan array ((1-2*x+2*x^2)/(1-x), x/(1-x)), except for the entry T(1,0). If this is correct then provided n =! 1 we have exp(x) * e.g.f. for row n = e.g.f. for diagonal n. For example, for n = 3 we have exp(x)*(1 + x + x^2/2! + x^3/3!) = 1 + 2*x + 2*x^2/2! + 4*x^3/3! + 8*x^4/4! + 15*x^5/5! + .... The same property holds more generally for Riordan arrays of the form ( f(x), x/(1 - x) ). (End)

A087699.name: Greater twin prime p such that 2^p-1 is composite.

A087700.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = smallest number such that the n-th partial concatenation has n divisors.

A087701.name: Maximal term in Collatz-iteration started at -1+2^n.

A087703.name: Primes whose digits can be partitioned (into at least two parts) into palindromes containing a palindromic part with at least two digits.

A087704.name: Number of steps for iteration of map x -> (5/3)*floor(x) to reach an integer > n when started at n, or -1 if no such integer is ever reached.

A087705.name: First integer > n reached under iteration of map x -> (5/3)*floor(x) when started at n, or -1 if no such integer is ever reached.

A087707.name: Number of steps for iteration of map x -> (5/3)*ceiling(x) to reach an integer > n when started at n, or -1 if no such integer is ever reached.

A087708.name: First integer > n reached under iteration of map x -> (5/3)*ceiling(x) when started at n, or -1 if no such integer is ever reached.

A087710.name: Least k >= 6 such that A087666(k) = n.

A087711.name: a(n) = smallest number k such that both k-n and k+n are primes.
formula: a(n) = A020483(n)+n for n >= 1. - _Robert Israel_, Sep 08 2014

A087712.name: a(1) = 1; if n = k-th prime, a(n) = k; otherwise write all prime factors of n in nondecreasing order, replace each prime with its rank, and concatenate the ranks.

A087713.name: Greatest prime factor of the product of the neighbors of the n-th prime.

A087714.name: Primes p = prime(i) such that p(i)# - p(i+1) and p(i)# + p(i+1) are both primes, where p# = A002110.

A087715.name: Table read by rows where i-th row consists of primes P of the form P=j*P(i)# -1 or P=j*P(i)# +1 with 0 < j < P(i+1). Here P(r)# = A002110.

A087716.name: Base-2 pseudoprimes (see A001567) of the form j*p(i)# - p(k) or j*p(i)# + p(k), p(i) and p(k) primes with p(i) < p(k) < p(i+1)^2 and 0 < j < p(i+1).

A087717.name: Start with x=n, then iterate the map x -> A322982(x) with A322982(x)=2*x-1 if x is noncomposite, otherwise A322982(x) = A032742(x), the largest proper divisor of x. If this iteration leads to a fixed point then a(n) is the value of that fixed point. If the iteration leads to a cycle, a(n) is the smallest value in the cycle. If the iteration never becomes periodic then a(n)=0.

A087718.name: Semiprimes with greater factor less than twice the smaller factor.
formula: a(n) ~ kx log^2 x with k = 1/log 4 = 0.7213..., see Decker & Moree. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jul 07 2016

A087719.name: Least number m such that the number of numbers k <= m with k > spf(k)^n exceeds the number of numbers with k <= spf(k)^n.
formula: Numbers so far satisfy a(n) = 3^n + 3*2^n + 6. - _Ralf Stephan_, May 10 2004

A087720.name: Repeated terms in the Hofstadter batrachian sequence A005185.

A087721.name: Strictly increasing domain of the Hofstadter batrachian sequence A005185.

A087722.name: Strictly decreasing domain set of the Hofstadter batrachian sequence A005185.

A087723.name: Values that appear more than once in A087724 (related to the growth of PrimePi).

A087725.name: Maximal number of moves required for the n X n generalization of the sliding block 15-puzzle (or fifteen-puzzle).
formula: Parberry shows that a(n) ≍ n^3, that is, n^3 << a(n) << n^3. In particular, lim inf a(n)/n^3 >= 1 and lim sup a(n)/n^3 <= 5. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Aug 23 2012

A087726.name: Number of elements X in the matrix ring M_2(Z_n) such that X^2 == 0 mod n.

A087727.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = (2 * (binomial(n,k)) * (n + 2 * k + 3)!)/((k + 1)! * (k + 2)! * (n + 3)!).

A087728.name: Table read by rows where i-th row consists of primes P of the form P=(j*P(i)#)^2 +1 with 0 < j < P(i+1). Here P(i)# = A002110(i).

A087729.name: Let X be the poset of finite subsets of the positive integers. The sequence is the number of downsets in X of cardinality n modulo equivalence by permutations of the positive integers.

A087730.name: Values of j for A087651 and A087732.

A087732.name: Smaller of twin primes of the form P=j*P(i)#-1 and P=j*P(i)#+1 with 0 < j < P(i+1), where P(i) denotes i-th prime and P(i)# the i-th primorial number A002110(i).

A087734.name: a(n) = f(f(n)), where f() = A035327().
formula: a(n) = 2*a(floor(n/2)) + n mod 2 - A036987(n) for n>1 with a(0)=a(1)=0.

A087781.name: Number of non-congruent solutions to x^2 - x - 1 == 0 mod n.

A087782.name: a(n) = number of solutions to x^3 + x == 0 (mod n).

A087784.name: Number of solutions to x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = 1 mod n.
formula: a(n) = n^2 * (3/2 if 4|n) * Product_{primes p == 1 mod 4 dividing n} (1+1/p) * Product_{primes p == 3 mod 4 dividing n} (1-1/p). - Bjorn Poonen, Dec 09 2003

A087785.name: Number of elements in GL(2,Z_n) x with x^2 == -I mod n where I is the identity matrix.

A087786.name: a(n) = number of solutions to x^3 - y^3 == 0 (mod n).
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = p^(2*floor(2*e/3)) + Sum_{i=0..floor((e-1)/3)} k*(p-1)*p^(e+i-1) where k = 3 if (p = 3 and 3*i+1 = e) or (p mod 3 = 1) otherwise k = 1. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Jul 17 2018

A087788.name: 3-Carmichael numbers: Carmichael numbers equal to the product of 3 primes: n=pqr, where p<q<r are primes such that a^{n-1} == 1 (mod n) if a is prime to n.
formula: n is composite and squarefree and for p prime, p|n => p-1|n-1. A composite odd number n is a Carmichael number if and only if n is squarefree and p-1 divides n-1 for every prime p dividing n (Korselt, 1899) n=pqr, p-1|n-1, q-1|n-1, r-1|n-1.

A087789.name: Smallest number greater than n having the same greatest prime factor as n; a(1)=1.

A087791.name: Indices n such that S^n(1) is an integer where S(x) = 3/2*ceiling(x).

A087792.name: Indices n such that S^n(1) is an integer where S(x) = 4/3*ceiling(x).

A087795.name: Minimal last term of an n-tuple of pairwise coprime composites in A.P.

A087796.name: Corresponding common difference associated with A087795..

A087797.name: Primes, squares of primes and cubes of primes.
formula: a(n) ~ n log n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Oct 19 2015

A087798.name: a(n) = 9*a(n-1) + a(n-2), starting with a(0) = 2 and a(1) = 9.

A087799.name: a(n) = 10*a(n-1) - a(n-2), starting with a(0) = 2 and a(1) = 10.
formula: Let F(x) = product {n = 0..inf} (1 + x^(4*n+1))/(1 + x^(4*n+3)). Let alpha = 5 - sqrt(24). This sequence gives the simple continued fraction expansion of 1 + F(alpha) = 2.09989 80642 72052 68138 ... = 2 + 1/(10 + 1/(98 + 1/(970 + ...))).

Also F(-alpha) = 0.89989 78538 78393 34715 ... has the continued fraction representation 1 - 1/(10 - 1/(98 - 1/(970 - ...))) and the simple continued fraction expansion 1/(1 + 1/((10-2) + 1/(1 + 1/((98-2) + 1/(1 + 1/((970-2) + 1/(1 + ...))))))).
Series acceleration formulas for sums of reciprocals:

A087801.name: Greatest common divisor of tau(n)+sigma(n) and tau(n)*sigma(n), where tau = A000005 and sigma = A000203.

A087802.name: Sum(mu(d): d nonprime divisor of n), mu=A008683.
formula: a(n) = if n=1 then 1 else A001221(n). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Oct 17 2003

A087803.name: Number of unlabeled rooted trees with at most n nodes.
formula: In the asymptotics above the constant c = A187770 / (1 - 1 / A051491). - _Vladimir Reshetnikov_, Aug 12 2016

A087804.name: Binomial transform of squares of Catalan numbers.

formula: a(n) seems to be asymptotic to c*n*log(n). Is c=log(2) ?

A087806.name: Inverse binomial transform of squares of Catalan numbers.

A087807.name: Prime factors of solutions to 24^n == 1 (mod n).

A087809.name: Number of triangulations (by Euclidean triangles) having 3+3n vertices of a triangle with each side subdivided by n additional points.
formula: A formula is given in the Bacher reference.
It seems that a(n) = Sum_{i, j, k>=0} C(n, i+j)*C(n, j+k)*C(n, k+i)). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Oct 25 2004; proved in the article by Asinowski et al.
G.f.: seems to be (10*g^3 - 17*g^2 + 7*g - 1)/((1-3*g)*(2*g-1)*(4*g^2 - 6*g+1)) where g*(1-g)^2 = x. - _Mark van Hoeij_, Nov 10 2011; proved in the article by Asinowski et al.

Conjecture: 2*n*(2*n-1)*(5*n^2 - 29*n + 30)*a(n) + (-295*n^4 + 1926*n^3 - 3425*n^2 + 2106*n - 360)*a(n-1) + 24*(3*n-4)*(3*n-5)*(5*n^2 - 19*n + 6)*a(n-2) = 0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 23 2015. Proved by Andrei Asinowski, C. Krattenthaler, T. Mansour, Counting triangulations of balanced subdivisions of convex polygons, 2016.

A087810.name: First differences of A029931.
formula: a(4n) = 1 - T(v_2(n)), else a(n) = 1, where T = A000217 (triangular numbers) and v_2 = A007814 (exponent of 2 in factorization of n).

A087811.name: Numbers n such that ceiling(sqrt(n)) divides n.
formula: Numbers of the form k^2 or k^2 - k. - _Don Reble_, Oct 17 2003
a(1) = 1, a(2) = 2, a(n) = n + a(n - 2). - _Alonso del Arte_, Jun 18 2005
G.f.: G(0)/(2*(1-x^2)*(1-x)), where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(2*k+1)/(x*(2*k+2) + 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 25 2013
a(n) = Product_{k=1...n-1}(1 + 2 / (k + k mod 2)), n>=1. - _Fred Daniel Kline_, Oct 30 2016

A087812.name: Sum of MoebiusMu for numbers between n and 2n inclusive.

formula: Conjecture: a(n) is asymptotic to n^c with c=0.677.... - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jun 05 2004

formula: a(n) ~ c * n log n with c = 0.07162.... [_Charles R Greathouse IV_, Dec 28 2011]

A087844.name: a(n) = a(a(a(min(n-1, abs(n - a(n-1)))))) + a(abs(n - a(n-3))).

A087851.name: a(n)=Abs(a(n-1)-floor(n*phi)), where phi=(1+sqrt(5))/2.
formula: a(1) = a(2) = 1; for n > 2, a(n) = |a(n-1)-floor(n*phi)|. - _Joshua Zucker_, Jun 16 2007

A087854.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) is the number of n-bead necklaces with exactly k different colored beads.
formula: T(n,k) = Sum_{i=0..k-1} (-1)^i * C(k,i) * A075195(n,k-i); A075195 = Jablonski's table.
T(n,k) = (k!/n) * Sum_{d|n} phi(d) * S2(n/d, k), where S2(n,k) = Stirling numbers of 2nd kind A008277.
G.f. for column k: -Sum_{d>0} (phi(d)/d) * Sum_{j = 1..k} (-1)^(k-j) * C(k,j) * log(1 - j * x^d). - _Robert A. Russell_, Sep 26 2018
T(n,k) = Sum_{d|n} A254040(d, k) for n, k >= 1. - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Aug 19 2019

A087855.name: a(n) = number of values k such that A086567(k) = n.

A087857.name: Primes of the form 16*m^2 + 25 for m=1,2,3,...

A087860.name: Expansion of e.g.f.: (1-exp(x/(x-1)))/(1-x).
formula: Sum_{n>=0} a(n) * x^n / (n!)^2 = exp(x) * (1 - BesselJ(0,2*sqrt(x))). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jul 17 2020
a(n) ~ n! * (1 - exp(1/2)*cos(2*sqrt(n) - Pi/4) / (sqrt(Pi) * n^(1/4))). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, May 10 2021

A087875.name: a[n] = pi[n-pi[n-1]] + a[n - a[n-2]], where pi(x) = number of primes <= x.

A087897.name: Number of partitions of n into odd parts greater than 1.
formula: Expansion of q^(-1/24) * (1 - q) * eta(q^2) / eta(q) in powers of q.
Expansion of (1 - x) / chi(-x) in powers of x where chi() is a Ramanujan theta function.
G.f.: Product_{k >= 1, k not a power of 2} (1+x^k).
G.f.: Sum_{k >= 1} x^(3*k)/Product_{j = 1..k} (1 - x^(2*j)). - _Emeric Deutsch_, Mar 30 2006

G.f.: 1/(1 - x^3) * Sum_{n >= 0} x^(5*n)/Product_{k = 1..n} (1 - x^(2*k)) = 1/((1 - x^3)*(1 - x^5)) * Sum_{n >= 0} x^(7*n)/Product_{k = 1..n} (1 - x^(2*k)) = ..., extending Deutsch's result dated Mar 30 2006. - _Peter Bala_, Jan 15 2021
G.f.: Sum_{n >= 0} x^(n*(2*n+1))/Product_{k = 2..2*n+1} (1 - x^k). (Set z = x^3 and q = x^2 in McLaughlin et al., Section 1.3, Entry 7.) - _Peter Bala_, Feb 02 2021

A087898.name: Choose a(n) so that 2*3*5*13*...*a(n) - 1 is prime; a(n) is prime; and a(n) > a(n-1).

A087902.name: Least m such that A080256(m)=n and has a maximum number A000792(n) of divisors.

A087903.name: Triangle read by rows of the numbers T(n,k) (n > 1, 0 < k < n) of set partitions of n of length k which do not have a proper subset of parts with a union equal to a subset {1,2,...,j} with j < n.
formula: T(n, k) = S2(n-1, k) + Sum_{j=0..n-2} Sum_{d=0..k-1} (k-d-1)*T(n-j-1, k-d)*S2(j, d), where S2(n, k) is the Stirling number of the second kind.
Sum_{k = 1..n-1} T(n, k) = A074664(n). - _Philippe Deléham_, Jun 13 2004
G.f.: 1-1/(1+add(add(q^n t^k S2(n, k), k=1..n), n >= 1)) where S2(n, k) are the Stirling numbers of the 2nd kind A008277. - _Mike Zabrocki_, Sep 03 2005

A087904.name: a(n) = the number of twin primes j*(p(n)#)+-1, for 1<=j<(p(n+1))^2.
formula: a(n) seems to grow like 16 log p(n).

A087907.name: Numbers n such that n*359# +-1 are twin primes, where 359# = 72nd primorial (A002110(72)).

It seems that the equality holds if and only if n = 2^m - 1 for some m. - _Jianing Song_, Feb 22 2020

A087911.name: Smallest prime p that is a palindrome in n different bases < p.

A087912.name: Exponential generating function is exp(2*x/(1-x))/(1-x).
formula: E.g.f.: exp(x) * Sum_{n>=0} 2^n*x^n/n!^2 = Sum_{n>=0} a(n)*x^n/n!^2. [_Paul D. Hanna_, Nov 18 2011]
Lim n -> infinity a(n)/(n!*BesselI(0, 2*sqrt(2*n))) = exp(-1). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Oct 12 2016
D-finite with recurrence: a(n) +(-2*n-1)*a(n-1) +(n-1)^2*a(n-2)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Feb 21 2020

a(0) = 5 and a(n) = n*Sum_{k=1..floor(n/4)} binomial(k,n-4*k)/k for n > 0. - _Seiichi Manyama_, Mar 04 2019
a((s+5)*n + m) = Sum_{j=0..n} binomial(n-j,j)*a(s*n+j+m) for all s > 0, m > 0.

A087981.name: E.g.f.: exp(-2*x) / (1-x)^2.
formula: Krauter and Seifter prove that the permanent of an n X n {-1, 1} matrix is divisible by 2^{n - [log_2(n)] - 1}.

Let c(n) be the permanent of the {-1, +1}-matrix of order n X n with n diagonal -1's only. Let a(n) be the permanent of the {-1, +1}-matrix of order (n+1) X (n+1) with n diagonal -1's only. Then by expanding along the first row (like determinant, but with no sign) we get c(n+1) = -c(n) + n a(n-1), a(n) = c(n) + n a(n-1), with c(2) = 2, a(2) = 2. {c(n)} has e.g.f. exp(-2x)/(1-x), see A000023. Also a(n) = c(n+1) + 2*c(n).

The following 4 formulas hold: a(n) = Sum_{k = 0..n} C(n, k)*D_k*D_{n-k}, where D_n = A000166(n); a(n) = n!*Sum_{j = 0..n} (n+1-j)*(-2)^j/j!; a(0) = 1, a(1) = 0 and, for n > 0, a(n+1) = n*(a(n) + 2*a(n-1)); a(0) = 1 and, for n > 0, a(n) = (n*(n+3)/(n+2))*a(n-1) - (-2)^(n+1)/(n+2). - _Vladimir Shevelev_, Apr 01 2010 [edited by _Michael Somos_, Jan 19 2011]
E.g.f.: 1/U(0) where U(k)=  1 - 2*x/( 1 + x/(2 - x - 4/( 2 + x*(k+1)/U(k+1)))) ; (continued fraction, 3rd kind, 4-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 28 2012
G.f.: 1/Q(0), where Q(k) = 1 + 2*x - x*(k+2)/(1 - x*(k+1)/Q(k+1)); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Apr 22 2013
G.f.: 1/Q(0) where Q(k) = 1 - 2*k*x - x^2*(k + 1)*(k+2)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 10 2013

G.f.: S(x)/x - 1/x = G(0)/x - 1/x, where S(x) = sum(k >= 0, k!*(x/(1+2*x))^k  ), G(k) = 1 + (2*k + 1)*x/( 1+2*x - 2*x*(1+2*x)*(k+1)/(2*x*(k+1) + (1+2*x)/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 26 2013
a(n) ~ sqrt(2*Pi) * n^(n+3/2) / exp(n+2). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Oct 08 2016
